# groups only lists the groups that the current or specified user belongs to / part of.
$ groups

# To create group
$ sudo groupadd -g 1009 negros

# -g for group id 
# negros is name of group 

# To check wether group is created or not 
$ cat /etc/group | grep "group_name"

Output :

root:x:0:

First column suggests group name
Second suggests password
Third suggests group_id
fourth column lists member which are part of that particular group

# To delete a group
$ sudo groupdel username


# getent - allows us to query a database
